            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "David Miller\u2019s appreciation for a well-balanced plate began not in a culinary school, but in the practical, suburban landscape of Evanston, Illinois. Raised by an accountant father and a teacher mother, his upbringing was one of pragmatism and stable choices. He loved the diverse flavors of nearby Chicago, a passion he filed away as a hobby while dutifully pursuing a business degree. He followed this sensible path to Northwestern for his MBA, landing a lucrative but sterile marketing job in corporate consulting.\n\nThe turning point came during a business trip to San Francisco at age 29. A spontaneous lunch at the Ferry Building was a revelation. Surrounded by artisan cheese, fresh oysters, and local wine, David saw a world where passion and business were not mutually exclusive. The city's vibrant, ingredient-driven food scene felt like a world he was meant to build, not just visit. Within a year, he had quit his job, taken a significant pay cut, and moved to the Bay Area, determined to break into the high-end hospitality industry.\n\nHe leveraged his business acumen to sidestep the kitchen line, starting in operations for a prominent restaurant group. His ability to analyze a P&L statement was as valuable as a chef's palate, and he quickly ascended. Now, as Director of Culinary Experiences for a major arts institution, he curates everything from gala menus to the caf\u00e9\u2019s daily offerings, blending artistry with economic viability.\n\nDavid lives in a tastefully minimalist apartment in Hayes Valley with his partner of eight years, Marcus, a landscape architect. His 5.1-mile commute on the Muni is a cherished ritual, a time to read and observe the city. Weekends are spent exploring farmers' markets for inspiration, hiking in the Marin Headlands, and perpetually researching the city\u2019s newest restaurant openings. While he\u2019s proud of curating experiences for others, David secretly dreams of creating his own\u2014a small, intimate wine bar, a place built less on profit margins and more on a perfectly paired conversation."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was 20, at a beloved Polish diner in Chicago with his father. While David tried to describe the earthy, profound comfort of the borscht, his dad was already calculating the tip to the penny. In that small moment, David felt a quiet schism: the world of ledgers versus the world of flavor. It wasn't defiance he felt, but a lonely ache. That feeling planted a seed\u2014a stubborn need to one day build a life where what he valued most had a justifiable place on the balance sheet.\n\n2.\nAge 29, during that fated lunch at the Ferry Building. It wasn\u2019t just the briny Hog Island oyster that changed him, but the vendor who sold it. The man spoke about the mollusk\u2019s terroir with the same fierce pride his mother used for her star pupils. For the first time, David saw passion not as a frivolous hobby, but as a viable, respectable business engine. The sterile certainty of his corporate life suddenly felt like a cage, and the vibrant, chaotic market felt like the only sane path forward.\n\n3.\nTwo years after moving to San Francisco, he found a celebrated chef staring grimly at a spreadsheet, ready to cut a beloved but unprofitable menu item. David, then a junior operations manager, stayed late and reworked the numbers, finding a new purveyor for one key ingredient. The chef\u2019s look of exhausted frustration softened into one of genuine respect. In that quiet office, David stopped feeling like an MBA impostor in an apron's world. He was a translator, bridging the gap between art and arithmetic, and he knew he was home.\n\n4.\nTheir third date, eight years ago. Marcus took him not to a restaurant, but to the Japanese Tea Garden as a light fog rolled in. Marcus spoke about how the landscape architect had designed the winding paths to force a slower, more deliberate pace. David was struck by how it mirrored his own philosophy of course-pacing a meal. It was the moment he realized Marcus didn't just see plants; he saw the architecture of experience. He knew then he\u2019d found someone who spoke his language, just in a different dialect.\n\n5.\nLast fall, on a weekend trip to Sonoma, they stumbled into a tiny, unnamed wine bar. The owner, an older woman, poured them a single, perfect Chardonnay and left them alone. The room was filled with the low hum of genuine conversation, not performance. Looking at Marcus across the small table, David felt a profound clarity. This was the true endgame. Not the grand galas, but a simple, intimate space built for connection. His secret dream stopped being an abstract fantasy and became a tangible, urgent goal."
